@* Sample plugin UI — rendered in its own AgentOS desktop window via DynamicComponent. This component
   ships INSIDE the plugin assembly (loaded at runtime from the host's plugins/ folder), proving a plugin
   can contribute a desktop window, not just services. Read-only: it uses only global shell CSS classes
   so it matches the desktop without referencing any host component.

   NOTE: interactive event handlers on a component loaded from a runtime-discovered assembly are not yet
   wired to the Blazor Server circuit — plugin windows are render-only for now (see the PR's deferred
   list). So this sample renders a static panel rather than a live input. *@

<header class="page-head">
    <div>
        <h1 class="page-title">Sample Plugin</h1>
        <p class="page-sub">A desktop window contributed by a runtime-discovered plugin.</p>
    </div>
</header>

<div class="metrics">
    <div class="metric">
        <div class="v">word_count</div>
        <div class="k">Tool contributed</div>
    </div>
    <div class="metric">
        <div class="v">DynamicComponent</div>
        <div class="k">Rendered via</div>
    </div>
</div>

<p class="muted" style="margin-top:14px">
    This window ships inside <code>AgentOs.Plugins.Sample.dll</code> — loaded at startup from the host's
    <code>plugins/</code> folder, with no compile-time reference from the host. The same plugin also
    registers the <code>word_count</code> tool; see the <strong>Plugins</strong> manager for the full list
    of what it contributes.
</p>
